  <p>Research published in <em>The Lancet</em> by Currie et al. identified a J-shaped relationship between HbA1c and all-cause mortality in people with type 2 diabetes — but importantly, the nadir of the curve (lowest mortality) was at approximately 7.5% in that treated diabetic population, with risk rising above and below this value. <sup><a href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/20149483/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">2</a></sup> For non-diabetic, healthy adults, population data consistently point to optimal longevity in the 5.0–5.2% range.</p>

  <p>The practical takeaway: a reading of 5.6% is technically "normal" by any clinical standard, but it represents a glucose environment that is meaningfully less healthy than 5.1% — and that gap compounds over years and decades into measurable differences in arterial health, brain function, and biological age.</p>
</section>

